event.description: One of the best “symphony films” of the ’20s and ’30s, this avant-garde travelogue explores the cobblestone streets and broken boulevards of anything-goes Paris. It screens with Viking Eggeling’s “Symphonie Diagonale” (1924), the last abstract short the filmmaker made before his untimely death.

He’s a complicated man, and nobody understands him but his lady. We’re not talking about John Shaft, but rather, Michael Jai White’s karate-kickin’ blaxploitation hero who’s out to avenge his brother’s death by getting even with—who else?—the Man. Trust us, a feature-length parody of guys mugging in Afros is not as funny as it might sound.
Seriously, is there a better screen entrance than the first appearance of Harry Lime, the black-market mover and shaker? And what about the “cuckoo clock” speech? Plus, that zither-heavy soundtrack!

And in those funny men march: Fatty Arbuckle (“The Rounders”), Charlie Chaplin (“The Knockout,” “A Night Out”), Buster Keaton (“The Butcher Boy”) and Max Linder (“Max et son chien Dick”), among others.

Two-hit wonder Corey Hart must be wishing he had the keys to that DeLorean right now; he reportedly turned down the part of Marty McFly (which went to Michael J. Fox), thus missing out on this Spielberg-produced smash. Still, he’s got his sunglasses at night. And he will never surrender.

Kermit travels from his home swamp to Hollywood, meeting pals like Fozzie, Miss Piggy and Gonzo along the way. Gratuitous star cameos and running gags abound (“Have you tried Hare Krishna?”), and the fourth wall is summarily demolished.

Warhol’s most commercially successful film (relatively speaking) actually features seven hours of footage; it runs only three and a half hours because two separate images are projected side by side. Music by the Velvet Underground sweetens the deal; if you’re an obsessive of all things Warhol- and Factory-related, you know you’re blocking the evening off for this.

There’s no descriptive information about the works by Polish director Zmijewski that are screening. (Titles include “Patricia,” “Yolanda” and “Them.”) But why not go for a blind buy? How often do you get the chance?

Before reggae became synonymous with the slow-and-low-end sound popularized by ’70s musicians in the Caribbean, the genre was characterized by quicker rhythms and tempos. They called it “rocksteady”; check out how this subtrend briefly dominated the island music scene.

The fact that a cult has sprung up around this rather derivative slab of Lynch-lite cinema is vexing enough. But getting a longer version of Richard Kelly’s little tale of apocalyptic dreams and awesome ’80s tunes is enough to tie our brains into knots. Still, for fans of the film, those 20 extra minutes must seem like a gift from the gods.

Prepare to gorge on early “Cinema Italiano!,” as Kate Hudson would say, with this impressive survey of the country’s celluloid output during the medium’s infancy. Silent comedies, historical epics, “diva films,” docs and oh so much more await you, paisan.

From a certain perspective, all of Kubrick’s movies—even 2001 and Dr. Strangelove—seem like horror films. When the director actually got around to making a proper thriller, he paradoxically produced the ultimate comic satire on the American family. With blood in elevators. Essential.

Located where Noho meets Soho, Zinc Bar is the place to hoot and holler with die-hard night owls. The after-hours atmosphere is enhanced by the cool mix of African, jazz and Latin bands.

Intimate NYC boutiques are to corner delis as Zoë is to a full-fledged supermarket. This Dumbo outpost for high-end garb, located in a cavernous former box factory, organizes a dizzying array of designers—among them Miu Miu, Zac Posen and Pucci—in its cement-floored space. Highlights at the satellite store (its flagship is in Princeton, NJ) include a Mayle sweaterdress , a cocktail number by 3.1 Phillip Lim and more than 18 denim lines. It’s a shame there aren’t discount coupons for this megamart.

Owner Clara Williams did what any eco-savvy girl would do after failing to find an organic soap she actually liked: She made her own. This cozy new shop offers an array of naturally scented oils ($20 each), soaps ($8 each), organic lip balms ($6 each), as well as toys for your animal friends ($8–$14). Shoppers can even peer into her studio and see where the handcrafted toiletries are made. Mention TONY to receive 20% off through December 10.
Subway: N, R, W to Prince St.

Opened in 2001 by red-hot hotelier André Balazs, Soho’s first luxury boutique hotel still has ample flourishes to keep it a notch above nearby competitors, which may be why celebs like Marc Jacobs and Mischa Barton favor it. The lobby, appointed with oversize white couches and chairs, and shelves lined with colorful books, acts as a bar, library and lounge—exclusive to hotel guests. The loft-like rooms are large by New York standards and feature furniture by Christian Liagre, enormous washrooms and Face Stockholm products. The restaurant, Mercer Kitchen, serves Jean-Georges Vongerichten’s stylish version of casual American cuisine. Secreted two levels down, the Submercer lounge recently reopened after five years. Rooms 75. Credit AmEx, DC, Disc, MC, V.
